solution:
We are asked to solve $27+2x=39$ for $x$.  We subtract 27 from both sides and then multiply both sides by $\frac{1}{2}$: \begin{align*}
27+2x&=39 \\
2x &= 12 \\
x &= \boxed{6}.
\end{align*}

We do some simplification, taking advantage of the fact that $n! = n\cdot (n-1)!$: \begin{align*}
\frac{9!\cdot 5!\cdot 2!}{8!\cdot 6!} &= \frac{9\cdot 8! \cdot 5! \cdot 2}{8!\cdot 6\cdot 5!}\\
&= \frac{9\cdot 2}{6}\\
&= \boxed{3}.
\end{align*}

