solution:
We can simply plug in $16^{\frac{1}{2}}=4$ and $625^{\frac{1}{2}}=25$ and get $4-25=-21$. Alternatively, recognizing the problem as a difference of squares, we can rewrite it as \begin{align*}
(16^{\frac{1}{4}})^2-(625^{\frac{1}{4}})^2&=(16^{\frac{1}{4}}-625^{\frac{1}{4}})(16^{\frac{1}{4}}+625^{\frac{1}{4}}) \\
&=(2-5)(2+5)\\
&=(-3)(7)=\boxed{-21}.
\end{align*}

We can expand the determinant as follows:
\begin{align*}
\begin{vmatrix} 0 & b - a & c - a \\ a - b & 0 & c - b \\ a - c & b - c & 0 \end{vmatrix} &= -(b - a) \begin{vmatrix} a - b & c - b \\ a - c & 0 \end{vmatrix} + (c - a) \begin{vmatrix} a - b & 0 \\ a - c & b - c \end{vmatrix} \\
&= -(b - a)(-(c - b)(a - c)) + (c - a)(a - b)(b - c) \\
&= \boxed{0}.
\end{align*}

